{#- DEFINITION — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-help-bankfeeds-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">&ldquo;Bank feeds not working,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A bank feed is the live connection between your bank or credit-card account and QuickBooks that downloads transactions automatically so you don&rsquo;t key them in by hand. When people say the feed &ldquo;isn&rsquo;t working,&rdquo; they usually mean one of a few things: new transactions have stopped importing or updating; the account shows as <em>disconnected</em> or asks you to sign in again; transactions are downloading <em>twice</em> (duplicates) or appear to be <em>missing</em> for a date range; or the bank is forcing a re-authentication after changing its own login or security.</p>
      <p>The good news is that most of these trace to a short list of causes, and the self-fix steps below address them in order of likelihood &mdash; re-authenticating the connection and manually updating the feed clears a large share of cases. What the steps <em>can&rsquo;t</em> fix is the bookkeeping damage a broken feed leaves behind: weeks or months of missing, duplicated, or miscategorized transactions, and a reconciliation that no longer ties. That part is a ProAdvisor job, not a reconnect. And if the underlying issue is your Intuit account, login, or an Intuit-side outage, that&rsquo;s Intuit&rsquo;s to resolve &mdash; not something we can reach.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

